# Architecture Plan (Issues #1-#18)

## 1) Module structure and file organization

### App layers
- Presentation (Next.js App Router pages/components):
  - `app/(public)/page.tsx` (home)
  - `app/(public)/posts/[slug]/page.tsx` (post detail)
  - `app/(admin)/admin/login/page.tsx`
  - `app/(admin)/admin/page.tsx` (dashboard)
  - `app/(admin)/admin/posts/new/page.tsx`
  - `app/(admin)/admin/posts/[id]/edit/page.tsx`
  - `app/not-found.tsx`, `app/error.tsx`
  - `app/layout.tsx`, `app/globals.css`
- API routes:
  - `app/api/auth/login/route.ts`
  - `app/api/auth/logout/route.ts`
  - `app/api/admin/posts/route.ts` (list/create)
  - `app/api/admin/posts/[id]/route.ts` (update/delete)
  - `app/api/admin/posts/[id]/publish/route.ts` (toggle publish)
- Data access:
  - `prisma/schema.prisma`
  - `lib/prisma.ts` (singleton Prisma client)
  - `lib/posts.ts` (post queries/mutations)
- Auth/session:
  - `lib/auth.ts` (password verify, cookie/session helpers)
  - `middleware.ts` (protect `/admin` excluding `/admin/login`)
- Config/validation:
  - `lib/env.ts` (typed env parsing)
- Shared types/utilities:
  - `types/post.ts`
  - `lib/markdown.ts` (render/sanitize helpers)
  - `lib/seo.ts` (metadata defaults)

### Conventions
- Use Next.js App Router + route groups `(public)` and `(admin)`.
- Keep server-only logic in `lib/*` and API routes.
- Use server components by default; client components only when interaction is needed (forms/editor).

## 2) Shared model/types

### Prisma Post model (Issue #2)
Fields:
- `id` (Int, autoincrement, PK)
- `title` (String)
- `slug` (String, unique)
- `content` (String) // markdown source
- `published` (Boolean, default false)
- `createdAt`, `updatedAt` (DateTime)

### TypeScript types
- `PostListItem`: id, title, slug, published, updatedAt
- `PostDetail`: full content + metadata
- `PostInput`: title, slug, content, published?

## 3) Dependencies between issues

### Foundation first
1. #1 Next.js + TS + Tailwind
2. #2 Prisma + SQLite + Post model
3. #3 Env config + `.env.example`
4. #4 Docker + compose

### Auth baseline
5. #5 Login API
6. #6 Admin login page
7. #7 Auth middleware
8. #8 Logout

### Admin CMS features
9. #9 Dashboard list
10. #10 Create post form + markdown editor
11. #11 Edit form
12. #12 Delete + publish toggle

### Public blog
13. #13 Public layout + global styles
14. #14 Home page published listing
15. #15 Post detail markdown rendering

### Polish/docs
16. #16 Error + not-found
17. #17 SEO + Open Graph
18. #18 README

Cross-cutting dependencies:
- #2 required for #9-#15
- #5-#8 required for #9-#12 admin routes/pages
- #13 should precede #14-#15 for consistent UI shell
- #17 depends on #13-#15 route structure/content

## 4) Key design decisions

- Auth strategy: simple admin session cookie (HTTP-only, Secure in prod, SameSite=Lax) backed by env credentials for single-admin use.
- Password verification: compare submitted password with hashed env value; avoid plaintext env storage.
- Slug handling: normalize on create/edit, enforce unique constraint at DB layer, show conflict errors.
- Markdown: store raw markdown in DB; render server-side to HTML and sanitize before output.
- API boundaries: write operations through admin API routes; read operations for public pages can use server-side data layer directly.
- Prisma client management: singleton pattern to prevent connection churn in dev hot reload.
- Error handling: typed error responses for APIs + Next error boundaries for UI resilience.
- SEO defaults: site-wide metadata in root layout; per-post dynamic metadata with OG tags from post title/excerpt.

## 5) Suggested package set

- Core: `next`, `react`, `react-dom`, `typescript`, `tailwindcss`, `@prisma/client`, `prisma`
- Auth/util: `bcryptjs`, `zod`, `cookie` (if needed)
- Markdown: `react-markdown`, `remark-gfm`, `rehype-sanitize`, `rehype-slug`
- Optional editor UI: lightweight textarea + preview initially, then editor package if needed

